(1) The generating function for $k$-combinations of a set $\{a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n}\}$ is given by:

\begin{align*}
(1 + x_{1} + x_{1}^{2} + \cdots) \cdot (1 + x_{2} + x_{2}^{2} + \cdots) \cdots (1 + x_{n} + x_{n}^{2} + \cdots)
\end{align*}

Expanding this product, we get:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{(1-x_{1})(1-x_{2})\cdots(1-x_{n})} = \sum_{k_{1}=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k_{2}=0}^{\infty} \cdots \sum_{k_{n}=0}^{\infty} \frac{k_{1}!\,k_{2}! \cdots k_{n}!}{k_{1}!\,k_{2}! \cdots k_{n}!} x_{1}^{k_{1}} x_{2}^{k_{2}} \cdots x_{n}^{k_{n}} }
\end{align*}

This is the generating function for the number of $k$-combinations of a set with $n$ elements.

(2) For the set $\{\infty \cdot a_{1}, \infty \cdot a_{2}, \cdots, \infty \cdot a_{n}\}$, the generating function is not well-defined since the elements are infinite.

(3) The generating function for $k$-combinations of $\{3 \cdot a, 4 \cdot b, 5 \cdot c\}$ is given by:

\begin{align*}
(1 + 3x + 3^{2}x^{2} + \cdots)^{3} \cdot (1 + 4x + 4^{2}x^{2} + \cdots)^{2} \cdot (1 + 5x + 5^{2}x^{2} + \cdots)^{1}
\end{align*}

Expanding this product, we get:

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{((1-3x)(1-3x^{2})(1-3x^{3})\cdots)^{3} \cdot ((1-4x)(1-4x^{2})(1-4x^{3})\cdots)^{2} \cdot ((1-5x)(1-5x^{2})(1-5x^{3})\cdots)} }
\end{align*}

This is the generating function for the number of $k$-combinations of the set $\{3 \cdot a, 4 \cdot b, 5 \cdot c\}$.

